               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="175310240014"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t17531024-37-person248">
                  Stephen 
                  Fladgate 
               <interp inst="t17531024-37-person248" type="surname" value="Fladgate"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17531024-37-person248" type="given" value="Stephen"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17531024-37-person248" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Conduit-street, Hanover-square, and keep a hosier's and haberdasher's shop; on the 29th of September, about two o'clock, as I was at dinner with my son and daughter in a back room, I saw the prisoner come into the shop, there were 6 pair of stockings which I left on the counter, and three yards of black ribband, three pair of which she took away with the ribband.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17531024-37-person249">
                  John 
                  Fladgate 
               <interp inst="t17531024-37-person249" type="surname" value="Fladgate"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17531024-37-person249" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17531024-37-person249" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner in the shop, and went out into the shop; and then went to call my sister, the prisoner was gone then; my sister look'd and missed three pair of stockings and the black ribband; so I went out after the prisoner, I saw her make a stop, and when she saw me coming she dropped the ribband, but the stockings she held under her arm.</p>
               <p>The prisoner had nothing to say in her defence.</p>
